<paragraph blockId="15.[189,1399,267,566]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
The present material falls within the known stratigraphic range of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[1080,1233,267,293]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiogaleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1080,1233,267,293]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ophiogaleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Sinemurian to Maastrichtian) (
<bibRefCitation author="Thuy B." box="[423,566,306,332]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 242" refId="ref13572" refString="Thuy B. 2013. Temporary expansion to shelf depths rather than an onshore-offshore trend: the shallowwater rise and demise of the modern deep-sea brittle star family Ophiacanthidae (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea). European Journal of Taxonomy 48: 1 - 242. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2013.48" type="journal article" year="2013">Thuy 2013</bibRefCitation>
), but extends the palaeogeographical range of the genus to polar latitudes. It furthermore stands out in representing the first finds of complete, articulated skeletons of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[225,378,384,410]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiogaleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[225,378,384,410]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ophiogaleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
providing insights into the previously unknown disc morphology and allowing to significantly extend the diagnosis of the genus. Since exhaustively known fossil ophiuroids play a pivotal role in phylogenetic estimates (
<bibRefCitation author="Thuy B. &amp; Stohr S." box="[668,915,462,489]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="0156140" refId="ref13724" refString="Thuy B. &amp; Stohr S. 2016. A new morphological phylogeny of the Ophiuroidea (Echinodermata) accords with molecular evidence and renders microfossils accessible for cladistics. PLoS ONE 11 (5): e 0156140. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0156140" type="journal article" year="2016">Thuy &amp; Stöhr 2016</bibRefCitation>
), the Spitsbergen 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[1137,1290,462,488]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiogaleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1137,1290,462,488]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ophiogaleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
material significantly adds to the dataset available for the systematic reconstruction of ophiuroid evolutionary history (
<bibRefCitation author="O'Hara T. D. &amp; Hugall A. F. &amp; Thuy B. &amp; Stohr S. &amp; Martynov A." box="[288,521,540,566]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="415 - 430" refId="ref12996" refString="O'Hara T. D., Hugall A. F., Thuy B., Stohr S. &amp; Martynov A. 2017. Restructuring higher taxonomy using broad-scale phylogenomics: the living Ophiuroidea. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 107: 415 - 430. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2016.12.006" type="journal article" year="2017">
O’Hara 
<emphasis box="[388,448,540,566]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,1399,609,948]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
In the original description of 
<taxonomicName authority=", Thuy (2013)" authorityName=", Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[551,870,609,636]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiogaleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[551,701,609,635]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ophiogaleus</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Thuy B." box="[719,870,609,636]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 242" refId="ref13572" refString="Thuy B. 2013. Temporary expansion to shelf depths rather than an onshore-offshore trend: the shallowwater rise and demise of the modern deep-sea brittle star family Ophiacanthidae (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea). European Journal of Taxonomy 48: 1 - 242. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2013.48" type="journal article" year="2013">Thuy (2013)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
postulated close phylogenetic ties with the extant genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Muller &amp; Troschel, 1842" authorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" authorityYear="1842" box="[352,820,648,675]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[352,505,648,674]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ophiacantha</emphasis>
Müller &amp; Troschel, 1842
</taxonomicName>
on the basis of similarities in lateral arm plate morphology. Indeed, the new insights on disc morphology of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[923,1073,687,713]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiogaleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[923,1073,687,713]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ophiogaleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fall within the spectrum of the extant members of the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ljungman" authorityYear="1867" box="[602,786,726,752]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophiacanthidae</taxonomicName>
as recently circumscribed by 
<bibRefCitation author="O'Hara T. D. &amp; Hugall A. F. &amp; Thuy B. &amp; Stohr S. &amp; Martynov A." box="[1151,1398,726,752]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="415 - 430" refId="ref12996" refString="O'Hara T. D., Hugall A. F., Thuy B., Stohr S. &amp; Martynov A. 2017. Restructuring higher taxonomy using broad-scale phylogenomics: the living Ophiuroidea. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 107: 415 - 430. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2016.12.006" type="journal article" year="2017">
O’Hara 
<emphasis box="[1249,1310,726,752]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al.</emphasis>
(2017)
</bibRefCitation>
with its 
<typeStatus box="[288,339,766,792]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">type</typeStatus>
genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" authorityYear="1842" box="[425,578,765,791]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[425,578,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ophiacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, due to the absence of family-level diagnoses for the new classification by 
<bibRefCitation author="O'Hara T. D. &amp; Hugall A. F. &amp; Thuy B. &amp; Stohr S. &amp; Martynov A." box="[392,644,804,830]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="415 - 430" refId="ref12996" refString="O'Hara T. D., Hugall A. F., Thuy B., Stohr S. &amp; Martynov A. 2017. Restructuring higher taxonomy using broad-scale phylogenomics: the living Ophiuroidea. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 107: 415 - 430. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2016.12.006" type="journal article" year="2017">
O’Hara 
<emphasis box="[490,552,804,830]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al.</emphasis>
(2017)
</bibRefCitation>
, it is currently not possible to provide compelling evidence in favour of such an assignment. 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[545,695,843,869]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiogaleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[545,695,843,869]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ophiogaleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
might, in fact, belong to a yet unknown extinct family sister to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ljungman" authorityYear="1867" box="[261,449,882,908]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophiacanthidae</taxonomicName>
. With the present knowledge at hand, however, the most conservative approach is an assignment to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ljungman" authorityYear="1867" box="[437,625,921,947]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophiacanthidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,1399,990,1212]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[189,339,990,1016]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiogaleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,339,990,1016]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Ophiogaleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. was probably a suspension feeder and used its long, robust, erect arm spines to trap food particles, as do some modern suspension-feeding ophiacanthids (
<bibRefCitation author="O'Hara T. D. &amp; Stohr S." box="[1028,1295,1029,1056]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="33 - 141" refId="ref12871" refString="O'Hara T. D. &amp; Stohr S. 2006. Deep water Ophiuroidea (Echinodermata) of New Caledonia: Ophiacanthidae and Hemieuryalidae. In: Richer de Forges B. &amp; Justine J. - L. (eds) Tropical Deep- Sea Benthos 24: 33 - 141. Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle 193, Museum national d'Histoire naturelle, Paris." type="journal article" year="2006">O’Hara &amp; Stöhr 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hess H. &amp; Meyer C." pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="29 - 40" refId="ref11897" refString="Hess H. &amp; Meyer C. 2008. A new ophiuroid (Geocoma schoentalensis sp. nov.) from the Middle Jurassic of northwestern Switzerland and remarks on the family Aplocomidae Hess, 1965. Swiss Journal of Geosciences 101: 29 - 40. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00015 - 008 - 1253 - 5" type="journal article" year="2008">Hess &amp; Meyer 2008</bibRefCitation>
). Its occurrence at shelf depths is not unusual as the late Jurassic was a time of exceptionally abundant and diverse ophiacanthid records in shallow waters (
<bibRefCitation author="Thuy B." box="[964,1105,1107,1134]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="1 - 242" refId="ref13572" refString="Thuy B. 2013. Temporary expansion to shelf depths rather than an onshore-offshore trend: the shallowwater rise and demise of the modern deep-sea brittle star family Ophiacanthidae (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea). European Journal of Taxonomy 48: 1 - 242. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2013.48" type="journal article" year="2013">Thuy 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Modern ophiacanthids are most common and diverse at bathyal depths, although shallower occurrences are not uncommon, especially at high latitudes.
</paragraph>
